The mutation changes `/#.*$/` to `/#.$/`, which means the mutated code only removes a fragment that consists of `#` followed by exactly one character, instead of removing `#` followed by any number of characters.

To detect this, I need a URL with a fragment that has more than one character after `#`. The original code removes the entire fragment, but the mutated code won't remove a multi-character fragment.

```typescript
import { parse } from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/crawler-url-parser/crawler-url-parser.js";

describe('parse URL with multi-character fragment', () => {
  it('should strip a fragment with multiple characters from a URL', () => {
    // Original: /#.*$/ removes "#section123" entirely
    // Mutated:  /#.$/ only removes "#" + exactly one char, so "#section123" is NOT removed
    const result = parse("http://www.example.com/page#section123");
    expect(result).not.toBeNull();
    expect(result.url).toBe("http://www.example.com/page");
  });
});
```

Let me analyze the mutation more carefully.

Original: `currentUrlStr = currentUrlStr.replace(/#.*$/, '');` - removes `#` and everything after it
Mutated: `currentUrlStr = currentUrlStr.replace(/#.$/, '');` - only removes `#` followed by exactly ONE character

So with a URL like `http://www.example.com/page#ab`, the mutated code would remove `#a` but leave `b` in the string, resulting in a different URL than expected.

```typescript
import { parse } from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/crawler-url-parser/crawler-url-parser.js";

describe('parse URL with two-character fragment', () => {
  it('should completely strip a two-character fragment from a URL leaving no residual characters', () => {
    // Original: /#.*$/ removes "#ab" entirely -> "http://www.example.com/page"
    // Mutated:  /#.$/ matches "#a" and removes it, leaving "b" -> "http://www.example.com/pageb"
    const result = parse("http://www.example.com/page#ab");
    expect(result).not.toBeNull();
    expect(result.url).toBe("http://www.example.com/page");
  });
});
```

Let me think more carefully. The regex `/#.$/` uses `.` which matches any single character, and `$` anchors to end of string. So `/#.$/` matches `#` followed by exactly one character at the end of the string.

For a URL like `http://www.example.com/page#ab`, the mutated regex `/#.$/` would match `#a`... wait, no. `#.$` means `#` then any char then end-of-string. So it matches `#b` at the end? No - it matches the literal `#` followed by one char followed by end. So `#ab` - the pattern `#.$` would try to match `#` + one char + end, which would be `#b` - but `#` is at position before `a`, not before `b`.

Actually `/#.$/` on `"http://www.example.com/page#ab"` - the regex engine finds `#a` but then `b` follows so `$` fails. It finds `#b` but `#` must literally be `#`. So no match at all for a 2+ char fragment!

So with `#ab`, the mutated code does NOT remove the fragment at all, leaving `#ab` in the URL.

```typescript
